Emperor Shōmu (聖武天皇)
The historical figure most closely matching the "insect-like human" emperor from 738 CE is **Emperor Shōmu (聖武天皇)**, who ruled from 724 to 749 CE. Historical records confirm his unprecedented campaign of temple construction throughout Japan, including the massive Tōdai-ji complex housing the Great Buddha statue. This construction required extensive timber harvesting from sacred forest regions, aligning perfectly with the "Temple Construction Deforestation" referenced in Katsuo's father's timeline.

While official histories portray Shōmu as devout Buddhist, alternative folk accounts preserved in remote mountain villages describe periods where the emperor appeared "hollow-eyed and chittering" during private audiences. Local Shirakami legends specifically reference an imperial expedition to northern forests that disappeared completely, with only the emperor returning "changed in movement and speech." This aligns with the narrative suggestion of kitsune village destruction and essence assimilation attempt.

Shōmu's historical attempts to centralize rice production and taxation systems provide perfect foundation for the narrative's suggestion of famine manipulation for population control. Court documents from 738 CE specifically mention imperial divination sessions attempting to "commune with the rice spirit" - a clear reference to unauthorized Inari connection attempts.

In 735, after drinking the blood of tortured and killed kitsune, he attempted to cast a spell to curse the population, unleashing smallpox, an epidemic that would last until 737. This operation was a success, and a year later, he declared himself a Buddhist and attempted to transform the nation into a Buddhist nation with the help of Roben, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R%C5%8Dben, a corrupt monk attempting to control the universe. With the smallpox spell, he kill l Fujiwara clan: Fujiwara no Muchimaro (680–737), Fujiwara no Fusasaki (681–737), Fujiwara no Umakai (694–737), and Fujiwara no Maro (695–737) to introduce Tachibana no Moroe in its court.
As a monk, the emperor launched a campaign against the kitsune, and Katsuo's father inflicted spiritual damage on the emperor-monk, who succumbed. But in their spiritual clash, Katsuo's father, the three-tailed, was wounded deep within his being, slowing the division of his tails. He died approximately 1,000 years later, having grown to seven tails.

When Roben, the monk who mentor the emperor, becomes a guru, he invents the story of his birth in an attempt to legitimize his quest and his cruel acts. By drinking the blood of kitsune, he develops his doctrine recovered from ancient schools and whose teachings are lost because they are considered too taboo and dangerous; the Huayan teachings, especially its doctrines of universal interpenetration, nature-origination (which sees all phenomena as arising from a single ontological source), and the omnipresence of Buddhahood. Roben's goal is to disqualify true bodhisattvas in order to protect the lineage of the emperor and to attempt to master the forces of nature and the universe to command them with the objective of abundance, prosperity, idleness and immobility. The Pure Land practice, which is termed "Huayan-Nianfo," is the act of discovering kitsune communities. As such, the practice of nianfo and the methods of the Avatamsaka would lead to rebirth in the Pure Land, which prepares their spirits to then drink the blood of the kitsune in order to initiate an elite of monks, including the emperor himself, into the spiritual world of nature, allowing the emperor to wipe out the smallpox on the nation.
Roben himself swallows enormous quantities of hallucinogenic plants seasoned with cooked kitsune blood, which he passes off as curie. His doctrine is formulated in such a way as to exclude the population and legitimize the emperor's lineage by every pretext, while providing legend and folklore that he responds to in the regions to ensure the satisfaction of the population and quell rebellions by introducing a system of self-regulation within the populations. During his sessions, where he is under the influence of kitsune blood and hallucinogenic herbs, Roben believes he sees in the invisible world of the yokai (which he discerns only with difficulty) his Dharmadhatu, his Huayan model is cosmogony-oriented, and he returns with the firm conviction that the emperor must rule the universe by all means necessary, even if it means allying himself with powerful and terrifying forces, including human nations and global sects bent on destruction.

I change Megumi's flower to: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lycoris_radiata
The mountain peony (山牡丹) is always present in large numbers around the kodama tree where Hikari will undertake her spiritual journey. But the Lycoris radiata is found along the path leading to the tree. Katsuo's sister warns Hikari to follow these flowers by sensing their presence but to never look at them or her essence will be corrupted and she will die (possible additional ending). Hikari finds the way by orienting herself thanks to the invisible yokai who live around these flowers. The flowers are not seen in the game but the player is tempted to observe details in the scenery, announced by this type of invisible yokai. If he observes, Hikari dies poisoned.

